arguments.file_text:
# Envoy HTTP Connection Manager — Test Coverage Gap Analysis

## Scope

This document analyses test coverage gaps across three core Envoy HTTP source files
and their corresponding unit-test suites:

| Source file | Lines | Primary test file(s) | Test cases |
|---|---|---|---|
| `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc` | 2,607 | `conn_manager_impl_test.cc` (5,407 ln) <br> `conn_manager_impl_test_2.cc` (2,271 ln) <br> `conn_manager_impl_test_3.cc` (2,903 ln) | ~223 |
| `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc` | 1,989 | `filter_manager_test.cc` | ~60 |
| `source/common/http/header_map_impl.cc` | 542 | `header_map_impl_test.cc` (1,091 ln) | 36 |

Analysis method: systematic cross-referencing of every non-trivial branch in the
three source files against the full body of unit tests, followed by targeted `grep`
searches to rule out incidental coverage.

---

## Gap 1 — Premature-RST detection and connection drain (`conn_manager_impl.cc:677–748`)

### Code under scrutiny

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:677-698
bool ConnectionManagerImpl::isPrematureRstStream(const ActiveStream& stream) const {
  absl::optional<std::chrono::nanoseconds> duration =
      stream.filter_manager_.streamInfo().currentDuration();
  if (duration) {
    const uint64_t lifetime =
        std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::seconds>(*duration).count();
    const uint64_t min_lifetime = runtime_.snapshot().getInteger(
        ConnectionManagerImpl::PrematureResetMinStreamLifetimeSecondsKey, 1);
    if (lifetime > min_lifetime) {
      return false;          // ← branch A: long-lived stream, NOT premature
    }
  }
  return !stream.filter_manager_.streamInfo().responseCode();  // ← branch B / C
}

// conn_manager_impl.cc:702-748
void ConnectionManagerImpl::maybeDrainDueToPrematureResets() {
  if (drained_due_to_premature_resets_) { return; }   // ← guard: never tested
  if (closed_non_internally_destroyed_requests_ == 0) { return; }

  const uint64_t limit = runtime_.snapshot().getInteger(
      ConnectionManagerImpl::PrematureResetTotalStreamCountKey, 500);

  if (closed_non_internally_destroyed_requests_ < limit) {
    if (number_premature_stream_resets_ * 2 < limit) { return; } // ← ratio branch
  } else {
    if (number_premature_stream_resets_ * 2 <              // ← limit-exceeded branch
        closed_non_internally_destroyed_requests_) { return; }
  }

  if (read_callbacks_->connection().state() == Network::Connection::State::Open) {
    stats_.named_.downstream_rq_too_many_premature_resets_.inc();
    drained_due_to_premature_resets_ = true;
    doConnectionClose(Network::ConnectionCloseType::Abort, absl::nullopt,
                      "too_many_premature_resets");    // ← drain action: never tested
  }
}
```

### Coverage status

`grep -rn "isPrematureRstStream\|maybeDrainDueToPrematureResets\|premature_reset\|PrematureReset"` across
`test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test*.cc` returns **zero hits**. Both functions
are called from `doDeferredStreamDestroy` (line 324) and `onResetStream` (line 391)
respectively but no unit test drives that call chain into either function body.
Coverage exists only in integration tests (`multiplexed_integration_test.cc`), which
do not exercise individual branches in isolation.

### Untested branches

| Branch | Location | Risk |
|---|---|---|
| `lifetime > min_lifetime` → returns `false` | :689–691 | Incorrect return value means good streams counted as bad |
| `responseCode()` present → returns `false` | :697 | Completed streams misclassified |
| `drained_due_to_premature_resets_` recursion guard | :716–718 | Stack-overflow protection unverified |
| `number_premature_stream_resets_ * 2 < limit` early exit | :731–733 | Drain triggered too early or too late |
| `doConnectionClose("too_many_premature_resets")` | :746–747 | Security-critical abort never unit-tested |

### Proposed tests

```cpp
// Test A: isPrematureRstStream returns false for long-lived streams
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, PrematureRstLongLivedStreamNotPremature) {
  setup();
  setupFilterChain(1, 0);
  // Advance simulated clock past the min_lifetime threshold (default 1 s)
  time_system_.advanceTimeWait(std::chrono::seconds(2));
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Return(FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration));
  startRequest(true);
  // Trigger an RST so doDeferredStreamDestroy runs
  conn_manager_->onEvent(Network::ConnectionEvent::RemoteClose);
  // number_premature_stream_resets_ must remain 0
  EXPECT_EQ(0U, stats_.named_.downstream_rq_too_many_premature_resets_.value());
}

// Test B: maybeDrainDueToPrematureResets triggers abort when ratio exceeded
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, MaybeDrainFiresWhenPrematureRatioExceeded) {
  TestScopedRuntime rt;
  rt.mergeValues({{"envoy.reloadable_features.http.premature_reset_total_stream_count", "4"}});
  setup();
  // Simulate 3 short-lived RST streams (no response code set → isPrematureRstStream=true)
  for (int i = 0; i < 3; ++i) {
    setupFilterChain(1, 0);
    EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, true))
        .WillOnce(Return(FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration));
    startRequest(true);
    conn_manager_->onEvent(Network::ConnectionEvent::RemoteClose);
    conn_manager_ = nullptr; // reset between streams
    setup();
  }
  EXPECT_CALL(filter_callbacks_.connection_,
              close(Network::ConnectionCloseType::Abort, _));
  EXPECT_EQ(1U, stats_.named_.downstream_rq_too_many_premature_resets_.value());
}

// Test C: drained_due_to_premature_resets_ guard prevents recursion
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, MaybeDrainGuardPreventsRecursion) {
  // After the first drain, subsequent calls must be no-ops
  // (verified by ensuring close() is called exactly once)
  EXPECT_CALL(filter_callbacks_.connection_, close(_, _)).Times(1);
  // ... drive two RST cycles after limit is hit ...
}
```

### Risk

**High.** The premature-RST drain is the primary defence against HTTP/2 RST-stream
flood attacks (CVE class). A regression in the ratio arithmetic or the recursion
guard could cause either a missed drain (leaving the server open to resource
exhaustion) or a crash via unbounded recursion.

---

## Gap 2 — `sendGoAwayAndClose` non-graceful path and `go_away_sent_` idempotency guard (`conn_manager_impl.cc:797–823`)

### Code under scrutiny

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:797-823
void ConnectionManagerImpl::sendGoAwayAndClose(bool graceful) {
  if (go_away_sent_) { return; }  // ← idempotency guard: only partially tested

  if (graceful) {
    if (drain_state_ == DrainState::NotDraining) {
      startDrainSequence();           // ← tested (graceful=true path)
    }
    go_away_sent_ = true;
  } else {
    codec_->shutdownNotice();         // ← NEVER called in any unit test
    codec_->goAway();                 // ← NEVER called in any unit test
    go_away_sent_ = true;
    doConnectionClose(                // ← NEVER called in any unit test
        Network::ConnectionCloseType::FlushWriteAndDelay,
        absl::nullopt, "forced_goaway");
  }
}
```

### Coverage status

```
grep "sendGoAwayAndClose" test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test*.cc
# Result: ONE hit at conn_manager_impl_test.cc:5278 — calls sendGoAwayAndClose(true)
```

The single existing test (`// Test graceful shutdown behavior with sendGoAwayAndClose(true)`,
line 5262) exercises only the `graceful=true` branch. The `else` block at lines
816–823 — comprising `shutdownNotice()`, `goAway()`, `go_away_sent_ = true`, and
`doConnectionClose("forced_goaway")` — has **zero unit test coverage**. The
idempotency guard (`go_away_sent_` check, line 800) is exercised only for the
graceful path; the guard for the non-graceful path is never triggered.

### Untested branches

| Branch | Location | Risk |
|---|---|---|
| `graceful=false` → `codec_->shutdownNotice()` | :818 | Protocol violation if codec not notified |
| `graceful=false` → `codec_->goAway()` | :819 | GOAWAY frame never sent |
| `graceful=false` → `doConnectionClose("forced_goaway")` | :821–822 | Connection not closed after forced GOAWAY |
| `go_away_sent_` guard when `graceful=false` called twice | :800–801 | Double-close / double GOAWAY |

### Proposed tests

```cpp
// Test A: non-graceful GOAWAY sends shutdownNotice + goAway + closes connection
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, SendGoAwayAndCloseNonGraceful) {
  setup();
  InSequence s;
  EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, shutdownNotice());
  EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, goAway());
  EXPECT_CALL(filter_callbacks_.connection_,
              close(Network::ConnectionCloseType::FlushWriteAndDelay, _));

  setupFilterChain(1, 0);
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Invoke([](RequestHeaderMap&, bool) {
        // Trigger forced GOAWAY from a filter callback
        return FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration;
      }));
  startRequest(true);
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->sendGoAwayAndClose(false);
}

// Test B: idempotency — second call with graceful=false is a no-op
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, SendGoAwayAndCloseIdempotent) {
  setup();
  // First call should fire codec methods exactly once
  EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, shutdownNotice()).Times(1);
  EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, goAway()).Times(1);
  EXPECT_CALL(filter_callbacks_.connection_, close(_, _)).Times(1);

  setupFilterChain(1, 0);
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Return(FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration));
  startRequest(true);
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->sendGoAwayAndClose(false);
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->sendGoAwayAndClose(false); // must be a no-op
}
```

### Risk

**Medium-High.** A filter using the non-graceful path to force-terminate a
compromised connection (e.g., after detecting a protocol-level attack) would silently
fail to close the connection. The idempotency gap could allow two GOAWAY frames
and two `close()` calls — a protocol violation and potential use-after-free.

---

## Gap 3 — HTTP/1.0 keep-alive response header (`conn_manager_impl.cc:1938–1948`)

### Code under scrutiny

```cpp
// conn_manager_impl.cc:1938-1948  (inside ActiveStream::encodeHeaders)
if (connection_manager_.codec_->protocol() == Protocol::Http10) {
  // No Content-Length → frame by close
  if (!headers.ContentLength()) {
    filter_manager_.streamInfo().setShouldDrainConnectionUponCompletion(true);
  }
  // If shouldDrain is still false (client sent Connection: keep-alive AND
  // Content-Length is present) → emit explicit keep-alive header
  if (!filter_manager_.streamInfo().shouldDrainConnectionUponCompletion()) {
    headers.setConnection(Headers::get().ConnectionValues.KeepAlive); // ← NEVER reached
  }
}
```

### Coverage status

All three HTTP/1.0 unit tests (`ResponseBeforeRequestComplete10`,
`ResponseBeforeRequestComplete10NoOptimize`, `ConnectionDurationSafeHttp1`)
respond with a status-200 that has **no `Content-Length`** header, so
`setShouldDrainConnectionUponCompletion(true)` is always called and the inner
`if` is never entered. The `setConnection(KeepAlive)` line at 1947 is dead in
every unit test.

### Untested scenario

A client sends an HTTP/1.0 request with `Connection: keep-alive`; the upstream
or a filter responds with an explicit `Content-Length`. Envoy must reply with
`Connection: keep-alive` to signal that the connection will persist. This branch
(line 1946–1948) has never been exercised.

### Proposed test

```cpp
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, Http10WithContentLengthAddsKeepAlive) {
  EXPECT_CALL(*codec_, protocol()).WillRepeatedly(Return(Protocol::Http10));
  setup();
  setupFilterChain(1, 0);

  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Return(FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration));
  startRequest(true);

  // Verify that Connection: keep-alive is set when Content-Length is present
  EXPECT_CALL(response_encoder_, encodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Invoke([](const ResponseHeaderMap& headers, bool) {
        ASSERT_NE(nullptr, headers.Connection());
        EXPECT_EQ(headers.getConnectionValue(),
                  Http::Headers::get().ConnectionValues.KeepAlive);
      }));
  expectOnDestroy();

  // Provide Content-Length so shouldDrainConnectionUponCompletion stays false
  ResponseHeaderMapPtr response_headers{
      new TestResponseHeaderMapImpl{{":status", "200"}, {"content-length", "5"}}};
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->streamInfo().setResponseCodeDetails("");
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->encodeHeaders(std::move(response_headers), true, "details");
}
```

### Risk

**Medium.** HTTP/1.0 persistent-connection support is rare but still used by some
legacy proxies and health-check agents. If this branch is broken, Envoy silently
drops the `Connection: keep-alive` header, causing clients to close and re-open
connections unnecessarily — a performance regression that is difficult to diagnose
in production.

