## Gap 7 — `checkAndCloseStreamIfFullyClosed` error-response half-close abort (`filter_manager.cc:1572–1584`)

### Code under scrutiny

```cpp
// filter_manager.cc:1572-1584
void FilterManager::checkAndCloseStreamIfFullyClosed() {
  ASSERT(filter_manager_callbacks_.isHalfCloseEnabled());
  if (filter_manager_callbacks_.responseHeaders().has_value()) {
    const uint64_t response_status = Http::Utility::getResponseStatus(
        filter_manager_callbacks_.responseHeaders().ref());
    const bool error_response =
        !(Http::CodeUtility::is2xx(response_status) ||
          Http::CodeUtility::is1xx(response_status));
    // Abort the decoder filter chain for error responses
    if (error_response && !state_.decoder_filter_chain_complete_) {
      state_.decoder_filter_chain_aborted_ = true;   // ← NEVER reached in tests
    }
  }
  // ... rest of half-close logic
}
```

### Coverage status

```
grep -n "allow_multiplexed_upstream_half_close.*true\|isHalfCloseEnabled" \
  test/common/http/conn_manager_impl_test*.cc
# All hits use {:status, "200"} — all are 2xx responses.
```

Every existing unit test that enables `allow_multiplexed_upstream_half_close=true`
sends a `:status: 200` response. `CodeUtility::is2xx(200)` is always `true`, so
`error_response` is always `false` and `decoder_filter_chain_aborted_` is never
set via this branch. The 4xx/5xx + half-close combination — a common upstream
error scenario — is completely absent from the test suite.

### Proposed test

```cpp
TEST_F(HttpConnectionManagerImplTest, HalfCloseWithErrorResponseAbortsDecoder) {
  TestScopedRuntime scoped_runtime;
  scoped_runtime.mergeValues(
      {{"envoy.reloadable_features.allow_multiplexed_upstream_half_close", "true"}});
  setup();
  setupFilterChain(1, 0);

  // Decoder filter will not send end_stream (simulating a slow upload)
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], decodeHeaders(_, false))
      .WillOnce(Return(FilterHeadersStatus::StopIteration));
  startRequest(false);  // end_stream=false from downstream

  // Upstream returns 503 — error_response=true → decoder chain must be aborted
  EXPECT_CALL(response_encoder_, encodeHeaders(_, true))
      .WillOnce(Invoke([](const ResponseHeaderMap& headers, bool) {
        EXPECT_EQ("503", headers.getStatusValue());
      }));
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], onStreamComplete());
  EXPECT_CALL(*decoder_filters_[0], onDestroy());

  ResponseHeaderMapPtr response_headers{
      new TestResponseHeaderMapImpl{{":status", "503"}}};
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->streamInfo().setResponseCodeDetails("");
  decoder_filters_[0]->callbacks_->encodeHeaders(std::move(response_headers),
                                                  true, "upstream_reset");

  // Verify stream is closed despite decoder chain not having observed end_stream
  // (decoder_filter_chain_aborted_ must have been set by checkAndCloseStreamIfFullyClosed)
  EXPECT_EQ(1U, stats_.named_.downstream_rq_5xx_.value());
}
```

### Risk

**High.** This branch is the mechanism that terminates a half-open stream when the
upstream signals an error. If `decoder_filter_chain_aborted_` is not set, the
stream remains open indefinitely (waiting for the downstream to finish uploading)
even though the upstream has already rejected the request. This is a resource-leak
vector: a malicious or malfunctioning client could tie up Envoy worker threads by
sending a slow body after receiving a 4xx/5xx response.

