## Gap 8 — `HeaderMapImpl::getExisting` lazy-map lookup path (`header_map_impl.cc:56–68`, `347–374`)

### Code under scrutiny

```cpp
// header_map_impl.cc:56-68  — lazy map construction
bool HeaderMapImpl::HeaderList::maybeMakeMap() {
  if (lazy_map_.empty()) {
    if (headers_.size() < kMinHeadersForLazyMap) {  // threshold = 3
      return false;   // ← the only path exercised in unit tests
    }
    for (auto node = headers_.begin(); node != headers_.end(); ++node) {
      lazy_map_[node->key().getStringView()].push_back(node);  // ← never executed
    }
  }
  return true;  // ← never returned
}

// header_map_impl.cc:361-374  — lazy-map lookup in getExisting
if (headers_.maybeMakeMap()) {               // ← always false in unit tests
  HeaderList::HeaderLazyMap::iterator iter = headers_.mapFind(key);
  if (iter != headers_.mapEnd()) {
    const HeaderList::HeaderNodeVector& v = iter->second;
    for (const auto& values_it : v) {
      ret.push_back(&(*values_it));           // ← never executed
    }
  }
  return ret;
}
// falls through to O(n) scan every time in tests
```

### Coverage status

```
grep -n "headers\.get(LowerCaseString" test/common/http/header_map_impl_test.cc
```

Every direct call to `headers.get()` (which invokes `getExisting`) in the unit
tests operates on a map with **at most two non-inline headers**:

- `Get` test (line 654): 1 non-inline header (`"hello"`)
- `CreateHeaderMapFromIterator` test (line 675): 1 non-inline header (`"hello"`)
- `TestAppendHeader` test (line 537, 566): 1 non-inline header (`"hello"`)

`kMinHeadersForLazyMap = 3`, so `maybeMakeMap()` always returns `false` in every
unit test that calls `getExisting`. The entire lazy-map branch (lines 363–373)
and the map-build loop (lines 62–65) are dead code from the test suite's
perspective.

Additionally, `HeaderList::remove()` (header_map_impl.cc:70–95) uses the same
lazy map: the `maybeMakeMap()` path at line 72 is also unreachable in the test
suite because no test calls `remove()` on a map large enough to trigger
map construction.

### Proposed tests

```cpp
// Test A: getExisting uses lazy map when >= 3 non-inline headers are present
TEST(HeaderMapImplTest, GetExistingUsesLazyMapWithThreePlusHeaders) {
  TestRequestHeaderMapImpl headers;
  // Add 3 non-inline (custom) headers to cross the kMinHeadersForLazyMap=3 threshold
  const LowerCaseString k1("x-custom-a"), k2("x-custom-b"), k3("x-custom-c");
  headers.addReference(k1, "val-a");
  headers.addReference(k2, "val-b");
  headers.addReference(k3, "val-c");
  ASSERT_EQ(3UL, headers.size());

  // getExisting must now build and use the lazy map
  auto result = headers.get(k1);
  ASSERT_EQ(1UL, result.size());
  EXPECT_EQ("val-a", result[0]->value().getStringView());

  // Verify lookup for a missing key returns empty via map path, not linear scan
  EXPECT_TRUE(headers.get(LowerCaseString("x-missing")).empty());
}

// Test B: remove() uses lazy map when >= 3 non-inline headers present
TEST(HeaderMapImplTest, RemoveUsesLazyMapWithThreePlusHeaders) {
  TestRequestHeaderMapImpl headers;
  const LowerCaseString k1("x-a"), k2("x-b"), k3("x-c");
  headers.addReference(k1, "1");
  headers.addReference(k2, "2");
  headers.addReference(k3, "3");
  ASSERT_EQ(3UL, headers.size());

  // remove() must trigger maybeMakeMap() and erase via map, not linear scan
  EXPECT_EQ(1UL, headers.remove(k2));
  EXPECT_EQ(2UL, headers.size());
  EXPECT_TRUE(headers.get(k2).empty());
  EXPECT_FALSE(headers.get(k1).empty());
  EXPECT_FALSE(headers.get(k3).empty());
}

// Test C: HeaderList::removeIf lazy-map branch (header_map_impl.h:241-272)
TEST(HeaderMapImplTest, RemoveIfUsesLazyMapWhenBuilt) {
  TestRequestHeaderMapImpl headers;
  const LowerCaseString k1("x-a"), k2("x-b"), k3("x-c");
  headers.addReference(k1, "1");
  headers.addReference(k2, "2");
  headers.addReference(k3, "3");
  // Force lazy map construction by performing a get() first
  (void)headers.get(k1);

  // Now removeIf must take the lazy-map branch in HeaderList::removeIf
  EXPECT_EQ(1UL, headers.removeIf([](const HeaderEntry& e) {
    return e.key().getStringView() == "x-b";
  }));
  EXPECT_EQ(2UL, headers.size());
  EXPECT_TRUE(headers.get(k2).empty());
}
```

### Risk

**Medium.** The lazy map is a performance-critical O(1) lookup optimisation for
requests with many custom headers (common in gRPC and internal service-to-service
traffic). An undetected regression in `maybeMakeMap`, `mapFind`, or the map-update
logic inside `HeaderList::insert`/`erase` could silently return stale or incorrect
header values without any failing test. The `removeIf` lazy-map branch
(header_map_impl.h:241–272) is separately untested and could corrupt the map if
the `pseudo_headers_end_` iterator is not advanced correctly during a removal.

